default7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRCC members work with thousands of refugee and migrant children each year, both children who are sep
defaultarated and children in families, and see the frequency with which these children’s rights are violated in practice. 
defaultMembers of the 
defaultconsortiu
defaultm have considerable expertise in
default supporting this group and offering a range of support, advice, advocacy and other services to them. RCC members try to resolve the issues faced by these children and families, preferring to find means of resolving 
defaultproblems that do not involve litigation wherever possible. However, from our years of experience of working with this group we know that legal representation is crucial if these children are to be able to realise their rights and solve the problems they fa
defaultce. In many 
defaultsituations legal representation is the only possible means of resolving the problem. Members of RCC who are not lawyers cannot lawfully provide advice on a child or family’s immigration issues (section 84, Immigration and Asylum Act 1999), nor 
defaultdo RCC members who are not lawyers have the necessary expertise to do so. Similarly in other areas of law such as community care or public law, 
defaultthe
default work that RCC members do relies on being able to refer to legal aid solicitors and we are extremely concerne
defaultd by the threat to legal aid provision, which in turn threatens our work, our ability to assist our clients, and could place a huge burden on scarce voluntary sector resources.
