default13.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Refugee Children’s Consortium strongly opposes proposals for limiting legal aid through a requirement that an applicant for legal aid is ‘lawfully resident’ in the
default 
defaultUK at the time of applying for civil 
defaultlegal aid and a requirement that the applicant has resided lawfully in the UK for 12 months. We also disagree with the rational
defaulte
default behind the proposal, which is that it will ensure that only those with a ‘strong connection to the 
defaultUK’ are able to benefit from
default the civil legal aid scheme. Many of the children with whom we work have a very strong connection to the UK. For some it is the only place they have ever lived, or the only one
default 
defaultthat they can remember. 
defaultFor example, there are an estimated 120,000 undocumente
defaultd migrant children in the UK, over half of which (65,000) were born in the UK to undocumented migrant parents
default and
default will fall foul of the residence test, as a
default child born in the UK does not automatically
default acquire British citizenship if
default their parent/s are not British. 
defaultIn addition, many undocumented children are brought into the UK by a parent 
defaultor guardian, or through a private fostering arrangement. Some come to the UK lawfully when they
default are very young with a parent or other relative and 
defaultgrow up here, unwittingly staying beyond the period when their visas or leave were valid. 
defaultIn some cases family relationships break down, leaving children abandoned and left to be taken into the care system.
